mple Bold (Lancashire), The Bold in Aston Botterell (Shropshire), Booden Farm in Haughton, Booth in Blithfield, and Bull Bridge in Penkridge (all Staffordshire). Compare   Bodle  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>bold</i>, Old English <i>b(e)ald</i> ‘bold, brave, noble’, which in Middle English developed the additional sense ‘arrogant, impudent, shameless’.","English: variant of   Bolt   and possibly a variant of   Bald   2."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Bolton was born in 1400, in Blackburn, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Bolton, was 20 and his mother, Lady Robert Bolton, was 15. He married Eleanor Aston in 1420. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1453, in Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1400–1453":"1400–1453","1400–1441":"1400–1441","1430–1482":"1430–1482","1380–1476":"1380–1476","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1400":"1400","1476":"1476","1420":"1420","1453":"1453","1430":"1430","1441":"1441","1385":"1385","1482":"1482","1380":"1380","Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Blackburn, Lancashire, England":"Blackburn, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"